34 (d) The commissioner shall provide guidance to districts related to the implementation
35 of this section,
36 including the distribution of information related to this requirement, reporting
37 requirements for school districts and required communications to parents and guardians related
38 to all financial aid options for high school students. Each district must annually report to the
39 department of elementary and secondary education by September 30 the following: (i) the
40 number of students completing and submitting the free application for federal student aid; (ii) the
41 number of students who received an exemption to this requirement through paragraph (iv)
42 subsections (b)(1), (b)(2) and (b)(3) separately and in combination, provided further that this data
43 be broken down by race, ethnicity, primary city or town of residence and such other categories
44 that the department may determine.
45 SECTION 2. Chapter 29 of the General Laws, as appearing in the 2022 Official
46 Edition, is hereby amended by adding the following section:
47 Section 2EEEEEE. (a) There shall be established and set up on the books of the
48 commonwealth a separate fund to be known as the FAFSA Trust Fund. The fund shall be
49 administered by the commissioner of elementary and secondary education. The fund may be
50 credited with: (i) revenue from appropriations or other money authorized by the general court
51 and specifically designated to be credited to the fund; (ii) interest earned on such revenues; and
52 (iii) funds from public and private sources such as gifts, grants and donations to aid districts in
53 supporting students, parents and guardians with Free Application for Federal Student Aid
54 submission. Amounts credited to the fund shall not be subject to further appropriation and any
55 money remaining in the fund at the end of a fiscal year shall not revert to the General Fund.
3 of 5

56 (b) Amounts credited to the fund may focus on underserved communities across the
57 commonwealth,
58 including those school districts with high concentrations of economically disadvantaged
59 students, and may be expended, without further appropriation, by the commissioner for the
60 following purposes: (i) to assist with the implementation and execution of section (a), including
61 staff and administrator training; (ii) for the development of workshops and other support services
62 and systems; and (iii) for the collaboration with stakeholder and community organizations to
63 support students, parents, and guardians with Free Application for Federal Student Aid
64 submission.
65 (c) Amounts received from private sources shall be approved by the commissioner of
66 elementary and
67 secondary education and subject to review before being deposited in the fund to ensure
68 that pledged funds are not accompanied by conditions, explicit or implicit, on the
69 implementation of FAFSA workshops or other programming that may be detrimental to students,
70 parents, guardians, school districts, or that places limitations or restrictions on how funds can be
71 used to support the implementation of this section. The review shall be made publicly available.
72 (d) Annually, not later than October 1, the commissioner shall report to the clerks of
73 the house of
74 representatives and senate, the joint committee on education and the house and senate
75 committees on ways and means on the fund's activity. The report shall include, but not be limited
76 to: (i) the source and amount of funds received; (ii) the amounts distributed and the purpose of
77 expenditures from the fund, including but not limited to, funds expended to assist school districts
4 of 5

78 in meeting the requirements in section (a); (iii) any grants provided to high schools and other
79 stakeholder organizations; and (iv) anticipated revenue and expenditure projections for the next
80 year.
81 SECTION 3. Section 1 of this act shall take effect on October 1, 2027.
82 SECTION 4. Section 2 of this act shall take effect October 1, 2026.
